[start section id="20102"]

Rectal cancer s/p neoadjuvant chemo/radiation therapy.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

29-yr-old male with diagnosis of rectal cancer in the setting of FAP and neoadjuvant chemo/radiation therapy completed elsewhere. He is the first member of his family diagnosed with FAP.  He had obstructive symptoms and required a diverting stoma at-home.  Pretreatment CT demonstrates large rectal tumor which may abut the prostate. On images he also is noted to have bulky mesorectal lymph nodes and a large left external iliac lymph node.
He came to RH Salt Lake City for second opinion for surgical options. He decided to seek surgical care at RH Salt Lake City.
Post-treatment pelvic MRI does not demonstrate invasion of the prostate. The post-treatment CT demonstrates some decrease in the size of the lymph nodes.  The left external iliac lymph node is bulky and abuts the iliac vasculature. Ultrasound of the liver did not demonstrate metastatic disease. He is anticoagulated for history of liver infarct. He has been transitioned from Coumadin to low-molecular-weight heparin with his last dose on 3/21/2010 in the evening. He comes to the hospital at this time for surgical management.

[end section id="20103"]

